10px;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Warrants</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A recurring theme of this c=
olumn is that if you have the power to make the price of a financial asset =
go up, you should (1) do that but (2) buy a lot of it first. So for instanc=
e Tesla Inc. is a big company and=C2=A0its chief executive officer, Elon Mu=
sk, is a famous influential guy with a lot of Twitter followers. So when Te=
sla announced that it would start accepting Bitcoin as payment for its cars=
, the price of Bitcoin went up. This was very predictable. So what did Tesl=
a do? It <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.=
267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDIt=
MDgvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXdvcmtzLWhpcy1tYWdpYy1vbi1kb2dlY29pbi1hbmQtYml0Y29pbg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf2e55f85" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> bought $1.5 billion</a> of Bitcoin=C2=A0<em>before=C2=
=A0</em>announcing the news, and then Bitcoin went up and it had an immedia=
te gain.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am a simple man and to me thi=
s seems good.=C2=A0Buy a thing, <em>create=C2=A0</em>good news for the thin=
g, announce that news, watch the price of the thing go up. In general I thi=
nk it is under-utilized, as a strategy. You don=E2=80=99t hear stories abou=
t, like, Moderna Inc. running a successful trial of its coronavirus vaccine=
 and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.2678=
71/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDMtMTkv=
Y3VyaW5nLWEtcGFuZGVtaWMtY291bGQtbWFrZS15b3UtcmljaA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B72b9e56b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> buying a ton of call options on cruise lines and airlines</a> before anno=
uncing the news. That would have been a good trade!</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Of course one has to be careful. Insider trading laws are complica=
ted, and you might worry that this trade =E2=80=94 you buy the asset when y=
ou know your plans=C2=A0and the market doesn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94=C2=A0raise=
s legal risks.[2] You might worry about market manipulation: If you do this=
 trade, you want to make sure that you=E2=80=99re doing something real to c=
reate economic value for the thing you=E2=80=99re buying, not just saying =
=E2=80=9CI like the stock=E2=80=9D to get a short-term pop. There might eve=
n be antitrust concerns, where one company buys stock of another company to=
 bet on the effects of the first company=E2=80=99s actions. And even=C2=A0i=
f it=E2=80=99s all legal, it=E2=80=99s potentially bad public relations, fo=
r reasons that are not fully intuitive to me. People seem to think that thi=
s trade is bad, because you know something that the market doesn=E2=80=99t =
know, and you use it to make a profit. Whereas I think that this trade is g=
ood, because you know something that the market doesn=E2=80=99t know, and y=
ou use it to make a profit.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amazon.com Inc.=
 is a big company, and if it decides to partner with a smaller company it c=
an steer a ton of revenue and attention to that smaller company. Amazon mig=
ht reasonably think =E2=80=9Cwe are sending all this revenue and attention =
to the smaller company, and they are going to profit from it, and we want t=
o extract as much of that profit as possible for ourselves.=E2=80=9D One wa=
y to do that is to set the commercial terms to be as favorable as possible =
to Amazon =E2=80=94=C2=A0pay suppliers as little as possible, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but arguably a better way to do it is to (1) cheerfully create val=
ue for the smaller company but (2)=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>some of that comp=
any first.[3] You bestow Amazon=E2=80=99s blessing on other companies, this=
 blessing makes those companies more valuable, and your stake in them benef=
its from your actions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLm=
NvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hbWF6b24tZGVtYW5kcy1vbmUtbW9yZS10aGluZy1mcm9tLXNvbWUtdmVuZ=
G9ycy1hLXBpZWNlLW9mLXRoZWlyLWNvbXBhbnktMTE2MjQ5NjgwOTk_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9=
eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe65043a9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">So</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The technology-and-retail giant has struck at least a dozen deals=
 with publicly traded companies in which it gets rights, called warrants, t=
o buy the vendors=E2=80=99 stock in the future at what could be below-marke=
t prices, according to corporate filings and interviews with people involve=
d with the deals.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amazon over the past deca=
de also has done more than 75 such deals with privately held companies, acc=
ording to a person familiar with the matter. In all, the tech titan=E2=80=
=99s stakes and potential stakes amount to billions of dollars across compa=
nies that provide everything from call-center services to natural gas, and =
in some cases position Amazon among the top shareholders in those businesse=
s.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The unusual arrangements offer another w=
indow into how Amazon uses its market heft to increase its wealth and clout=
. The company has been under growing scrutiny from regulators and lawmakers=
 over its competitive practices, including with companies it partners with.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While the deals can benefit the suppliers =
by locking in big contracts, which can also boost their share prices, execu=
tives at several of the companies said they felt they couldn=E2=80=99t refu=
se Amazon=E2=80=99s push for the right to buy the stock without risking a m=
ajor contract. The deals in some cases also give Amazon rights such as boar=
d representation and the ability to top any acquisition offers from other c=
ompanies.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For Amazon, the arrangements give=
 it a piece of the potential upside their vendors can get from doing busine=
ss with one of the world=E2=80=99s biggest companies.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Grocery distributor SpartanNash Co. last year amended a contract wit=
h Amazon to deliver groceries to its Amazon Fresh arm. The Grand Rapids, Mi=
ch.-based company had been supplying Amazon with food since 2016, but this =
time Amazon added a condition: if it bought $8 billion worth of groceries o=
ver seven years, it could get warrants to purchase around 15% of SpartanNas=
h=E2=80=99s stock at a price potentially lower than the market. Amazon also=
 said it wanted to be notified of any takeover offers for SpartanNash and h=
ave a 10-day window to offer a counterbid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
SpartanNash executives were taken aback, said people familiar with the matt=
er. No customer had requested such terms before. Executives ultimately deci=
ded they didn=E2=80=99t want to haggle with one of SpartanNash=E2=80=99s bi=
ggest customers, and that being tied to Amazon could raise their company=E2=
=80=99s profile, one of the people said.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Well, look, here is a graph of SpartanNash=E2=80=99s stock=
 price over the last year:</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iXCPOhcxWJt8/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/iXCPOhcxWJt8/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Can you spot the day that SpartanN=
ash <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.26787=
1/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODc3NDIyL=
zAwMDE1NjQ1OTAyMDA0NjE0NC9zcHRuLThrXzIwMjAxMDA3Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBe69b736f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">announced its Amazon contract</a>? I bet you can! The stock was up 26.3=
% that day. SpartanNash added 26.3% to its equity market value, in exchange=
 for giving as much as 15% of its equity market value to Amazon. Twenty-six=
 is more than 15.[4] Seems like a good trade for both of them? Obviously Sp=
artanNash would have preferred to add 26.3% to its market cap=C2=A0<em>with=
out=C2=A0</em>giving any of it to Amazon, but that deal wasn=E2=80=99t on t=
he table. Also it is quite possible that what =E2=80=9Craised their company=
=E2=80=99s profile=E2=80=9D is not=C2=A0<em>just=C2=A0</em>the commercial a=
greement but=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>the warrants, that being part-owned by=
 Amazon made it more valuable than merely being an Amazon supplier would.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amazon=E2=80=99s reasoning seems to be expli=
citly about capturing the upside that it creates in smaller companies:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amazon=E2=80=99s first major warran=
ts deal with a publicly traded vendor came in 2016. Amazon was seeking a pa=
rtner with cargo planes to help build out its massive logistics network. Ex=
ecutives reasoned that the company=E2=80=99s potential partners were all sm=
aller, lesser-known companies with stagnant growth, and that a major contra=
ct from Amazon would invigorate their stocks, according to a person familia=
r with the matter. Amazon wanted some of that potential upside, the person =
said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That reasoning strikes m=
e as completely correct and kind of obvious. Yet somehow this approach is n=
ot popular; it is viewed as grasping and excessive and monopolistic. And I =
suppose Amazon=E2=80=99s competitive advantage is in part that it does the =
economically obvious thing even if that seems grasping and excessive and mo=
nopolistic.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh one other very niche thing t=
hat I enjoyed is that Amazon=E2=80=99s warrants appear to be based on the U=
.S. Treasury=E2=80=99s Troubled Asset Relief Program warrants:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Former Amazon executives who worked on warr=
ant deals said they found no direct precedent before the company began stri=
king them. For a guide, an Amazon team sleuthed through financial documents=
 from the 2008 financial crisis to find information about bank bailouts tha=
t involved warrants, one of the people said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">I used to (very) occasionally create warrants, as an equity-=
linked investment banker, and I will say that =E2=80=9Cjust copy the TARP w=
arrants=E2=80=9D was kind of the=C2=A0standard approach. Arguably Treasury,=
 in turn, was influenced by Berkshire Hathaway Inc.=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4Njk4Mi8wMDAwOTUwMTIzMDgwMTE3MjAveT=
cxNDgwZXh2M3cxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfa0ec82a" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">preferred-stock-plus-warrants=
 investment</a> in Goldman Sachs Group Inc. a few weeks before the <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4Njk4Mi8wMDAwOTUwMTIzMDgwMTQw=
ODUveTcyMTcyZTh2ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30acd201" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">TARP deals</a>, and the Be=
rkshire deal is also a popular=C2=A0precedent. These are good examples of m=
y general rule, that if you can create a ton of value for another company y=
ou should buy its stock first. Warren Buffett, famously, provides a halo of=
 folksy value-investing goodness to the companies he supports; buying warra=
nts from Goldman let him monetize that halo. And when the U.S. government s=
tepped in to support the big banks in the fall of 2008, it was sending a st=
rong signal to the effect of =E2=80=9Cunlike Lehman, we=E2=80=99re not goin=
g to let the banks that take TARP money go under.=E2=80=9D Good for the sto=
ck price! Might as well get some warrants for that.</p><h2 style=3D"font-we=
ight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-se=
rif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">Bigness</h2><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some banks are very big. Some people think this =
is bad. There is a traditional way to say =E2=80=9Cit is bad that this comp=
any is so big,=E2=80=9D and that way uses the word =E2=80=9Cmonopoly.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThis company is so big that it is a monopoly, which is ba=
d.=E2=80=9D It is useful to be able to say this, because the government has=
 a lot of power to limit monopolies, to regulate their behavior and break t=
hem up.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not, however, particula=
rly true of the big banks. A monopoly is a specific thing, a company that i=
s so big that it dominates its market and can force out competitors and rai=
se prices. The markets in which banks compete are, for the most part, extre=
mely competitive.[5] If you want a mortgage, you pretty much pay the market=
 rate for mortgages; JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. can=E2=80=99t charge you what=
ever it wants.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, people think it is ba=
d that the banks are so big, for other reasons. They worry about risk conce=
ntration, about banks that are =E2=80=9Ctoo big to fail=E2=80=9D taking too=
 many risks and the taxpayers bearing those risks, about too much centraliz=
ation of banking making it more fragile, about banks that are =E2=80=9Ctoo =
big to manage=E2=80=9D doing dumb things and crashing the financial system.=
 Those worries are controversial, but never mind that. Assume for now that =
they are correct. What should the government do about them?</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">One possibility is that the government=E2=80=99s antitrust=
 regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0at the Justice Department and the Federal Trade =
Commission =E2=80=94=C2=A0should go after the biggest banks for antitrust v=
iolations. The regulators could say =E2=80=9Cyou are too big, you are a mon=
opoly, we need to break you up into smaller pieces.=E2=80=9D And then the b=
anks would say =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D and they would go to court, and the re=
gulators could try to prove that the big banks are monopolists. And this wo=
uld be hard to do, because they basically aren=E2=80=99t. It wouldn=E2=80=
=99t be impossible, though, I guess, because they are in lots of businesses=
 and some of them are less competitive than others and there are probably s=
ome bad emails somewhere and so forth. The regulators=E2=80=99 odds of brea=
king up the big banks on antitrust grounds wouldn=E2=80=99t be=C2=A0<em>zer=
o</em>. But they would be low.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other po=
ssibility is that <em>other</em> government regulators should, in setting <=
em>other</em> regulations, take bigness into account and try to regulate an=
d discourage it. Conveniently banking is a very regulated business, and the=
re are regulators and prudential supervisors who can do all sorts of meddli=
ng in a bank=E2=80=99s business. So for instance if you worried that giant =
banks could be =E2=80=9Ctoo big to fail=E2=80=9D and pose a systemic risk t=
o the financial system, the banks=E2=80=99 capital regulators could put out=
 a rule saying =E2=80=9Cvery big banks need to have more capital to offset =
the higher risk they pose to the financial system.=E2=80=9D That would both=
 reduce the risk of big-bank failure and also create an incentive for banks=
 to stay smaller or break themselves up. And in fact there is such a rule, =
for exactly those sorts of reasons; it is=C2=A0called the =E2=80=9C<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L2Vjb25yZXMvbm90ZXMvZmVkcy1ub3Rlcy9ob3ctZG8t=
dXMtZ2xvYmFsLXN5c3RlbWljYWxseS1pbXBvcnRhbnQtYmFua3MtbG93ZXItdGhlaXItY2FwaXR=
hbC1zdXJjaGFyZ2VzLTIwMjAwMTMxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB417b845f" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">G-SIB surcharg=
e</a>.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or if you worried that gian=
t banks could be =E2=80=9Ctoo big to manage=E2=80=9D and do dumb things, th=
en the banks=E2=80=99=C2=A0supervisors=C2=A0could tell a big bank that did =
a dumb thing =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t get any bigger until we=E2=80=99re =
satisfied you won=E2=80=99t do more dumb things.=E2=80=9D They can just do =
that! The supervisors can just=C2=A0<em>tell a bank not to get bigger</em>,=
 and it has to listen! They actually <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDItMDUvd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tbXVzdC1iZS1iZXR0ZXItYmVmb3J=
lLWl0LWdldHMtYmlnZ2Vy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBebc60411" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> did it to Wells Fargo &amp;=
 Co.</a>, it=E2=80=99s kind of amazing. The theory wasn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9C=
Wells Fargo is a monopoly=E2=80=9D; it was just =E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t l=
ike what Wells Fargo has been up to so it can=E2=80=99t get any bigger.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should emphasize that banking is a=
=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>regulated business, and the government doesn=E2=80=
=99t have quite as many levers to pull with most other=C2=A0businesses. Sti=
ll lots of businesses are regulated in lots of ways, and the same general p=
rinciples apply:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you think it i=
s bad that a business is big, because it has a monopoly, sure, have the ant=
itrust regulators go after it for antitrust violations.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you think it is bad that a business is big, for=C2=
=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>reasons, have=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>regulators tr=
y to limit its bigness in ways that directly address those other reasons.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In a pinch, if you think it is bad =
that a business is big, you could always have the other regulators try to l=
imit its bigness in ways that=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>relate in an=
y particularly logical way to those reasons. If you think that the bigness =
of social media companies=C2=A0is bad because they spread=C2=A0misinformati=
on and undermine=C2=A0democracy, that is not really an antitrust problem,[6=
] and there is not exactly a Federal Truth Regulator that can promulgate mi=
sinformation rules. But maybe you can find some regulatory regime to shoeho=
rn into that purpose. Maybe you=E2=80=99ve got a regulator in charge of, I =
don=E2=80=99t know, internet bandwidth or wireless spectrum or electricity =
usage or truth in advertising or whatever,[7] and you tell that regulator t=
o turn up the heat on big social media companies. Not because you care abou=
t their electricity usage or whatever, but just to deter them from being bi=
g, because you think their bigness is bad.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">If all else fails, you can have the antitrust regulators try to br=
eak up the business because it is too big, even though it isn=E2=80=99t a m=
onopoly. That may not work though.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjkvZmFj=
