=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked yesterday<=
/a> about Facebook Inc. Lots of people think it is bad that Facebook is so =
big, but it is a little hard to put that in traditional monopoly terms. Is =
the problem of Facebook=E2=80=99s bigness that it can charge users monopoli=
stically high prices for posting on Facebook? No; posting on Facebook is fr=
ee. Is the problem that it can charge advertisers monopolistically high pri=
ces for advertising on Facebook? No. I don=E2=80=99t know if it can; I just=
 know that I have never heard anyone make that complaint: If you don=E2=80=
=99t like Facebook, it=E2=80=99s not because you worry about <em>advertiser=
s overpaying</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is the problem of Facebo=
ok=E2=80=99s bigness some=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>form of anticompetitive =
behavior that makes consumers (Facebook users) worse off? Sure, maybe; intu=
itively I suspect Instagram would be a nicer place if it was still independ=
ent than it is under Facebook=E2=80=99s ownership. But this stuff is a litt=
le hard to articulate, which is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fyd=
GljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMzAvZnRjLXJldml2YWwtb2YtZmFjZWJvb2stY2FzZS1oaW5nZXMtb24t=
Ym9sc3RlcmluZy1tb25vcG9seS1jbGFpbQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4cbc9e6e" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> why the FTC fa=
iled to articulate it</a>: It sued Facebook for antitrust violations, and t=
his week a judge dismissed that lawsuit for failing to even say why Faceboo=
k might have a monopoly. =E2=80=9CIt is almost as if the agency expects the=
 Court to simply nod to the conventional wisdom that Facebook is a monopoli=
st,=E2=80=9D wrote the judge. The conventional wisdom is that it is bad tha=
t Facebook is so big! But that does not make it a monopoly in the technical=
, legal sense of the term.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suspect the ma=
in problem most people have with Facebook=E2=80=99s bigness is not about co=
nsumer choice but rather about Facebook=E2=80=99s political and social infl=
uence. You could imagine addressing that more directly than with antitrust =
law. And there have been suggestions for doing so =E2=80=94=C2=A0repealing =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aH=
