om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Speaking of antitrust</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjQvYXJjaGVnb3Mtcy1iYW5rcy1=
zYWlkLXRvLWZhY2UtZG9qLWFudGl0cnVzdC1wcm9iZS1pbnRvLWNvbGxhcHNl/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB1d5195b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> This is from last week</a> but we didn=E2=80=99t talk about i=
t then and it=E2=80=99s interesting:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">U.S. investigators who focus on corporate collusion are examining how=
 global banks handled multibillion-dollar trades with Archegos Capital Mana=
gement that sent stocks into a spiral and burned other shareholders.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Justice Department=E2=80=99s antitrust divisi=
on is handling at least part of the probe into the collapse of Bill Hwang=
=E2=80=99s firm after lenders rushed to liquidate souring positions in Marc=
h, according to people familiar with the matter. The debacle also erased mu=
ch of the billionaire owner=E2=80=99s fortune and saddled banks with more t=
han $10 billion in losses.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The division has=
 been seeking information from Hwang=E2=80=99s biggest backers on Wall Stre=
et, who had discussed the possibility of moving in concert to unwind the po=
rtfolio and sever ties with his busted family office, the people said, aski=
ng not to be identified because they aren=E2=80=99t authorized to discuss t=
he inquiries. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the root of the collap=
se were Archegos=E2=80=99s massive bets on certain stocks, such as media co=
mpanies ViacomCBS Inc. and Discovery Inc., as well as Chinese tech darling =
Baidu Inc. Banks provided billions of dollars in leverage, eager to reap fe=
es handling the investment firm=E2=80=99s burgeoning portfolio. But as the =
positions started to sour, Archegos was unable to meet margin calls, and ba=
nkers soon realized the extent to which it had placed parallel positions wi=
th competitors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1=
zLWFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhcmQtZm9yLWJhbmtz/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBeabf38eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> stylized popular story</a> of Archegos is that it had enormou=
s levered stock positions with half a dozen big banks, but because it did t=
hose trades via swaps, nobody knew about it. Each bank thought =E2=80=9Cwe =
own a lot of stock for these Archegos guys huh,=E2=80=9D but no bank knew t=
hat a bunch of <em>other</em> banks also owned a lot of stock for Archegos.=
 Then one day some of the stocks went down, the banks asked Archegos to pos=
t more money, and Archegos replied =E2=80=9Cnope, we=E2=80=99re fresh out o=
f money, also by the way we=E2=80=99ve got these same huge positions on wit=
h a bunch of other banks, okay, have fun with that, bye!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the banks called the other banks and =
were like =E2=80=9Cwait were you lending Archegos billions of dollars to bu=
y ViacomCBS and Discovery?=E2=80=9D and the other banks were like =E2=80=9C=
yes, wait, were=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>lending Archegos billions of dollars=
 to buy ViacomCBS and Discovery?=E2=80=9D And they realized they had a prob=
lem, which was that they all owned billions of dollars of ViacomCBS and Dis=
covery that they didn=E2=80=99t want, and that the prices of those stocks h=
ad been pushed up to irrational levels by Archegos buying all of them.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the banks got together and said, look, w=
e could all sell these stocks that we don=E2=80=99t want now, but that will=
 push their prices way down and we will all lose a ton of money. Or we coul=
d=C2=A0<em>wait=C2=A0</em>and sell them over time, rather than dumping them=
 in a fire sale, and the result will be that markets will be more orderly a=
nd rational and also we won't lose so much money. But we have to all agree =
to do that together, because if most of us wait but some of us sell early, =
the ones who sell early will do well=C2=A0but the rest of us will be hosed.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Goldman Sachs heard =E2=80=9Cthe ones =
who sell early will do well but the rest of us will be hosed,=E2=80=9D and =
its ears perked up, because Goldman loves (1) doing well and (2) hosing its=
 competitors, so Goldman dumped its Archegos-linked stocks and did well, an=
d the coordination broke up and everyone ended up dumping their stocks in a=
 fire sale that crashed the market for those stocks and generally freaked o=
ut the market.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know how acc=
urate this narrative is in its details but it seems to be the conventional =
wisdom about Archegos. In particular, the part about all the banks getting =
on the phone to discuss not selling stock to keep the prices high is very m=
uch a part of the story. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/24317788.267871/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMjkvYmFuay1iaWNrZXJpbmctZGV2b2x2ZWQtaW50by1tYWQtZGFzaC1=
0by11bmxvYWQtYXJjaGVnb3Mtc3RvY2tz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd281de90" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s story from March</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Glob=
al investment banks, gathering in a hastily arranged call, needed a swift t=
ruce to deal with Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s Archegos Capital Management if they =
were to head off billions of dollars in losses for banks and a potential ch=
ain reaction across markets. Yet by Friday, it was everyone for themselves.=
 ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Emissaries from several of the world=
=E2=80=99s biggest prime brokerages tried to head off the chaos by holding =
a call with Hwang before the drama spilled into public view Friday morning.=
 The idea, pushed by Credit Suisse, was to reach some sort of temporary sta=
ndstill to figure out how to untie positions without sparking panic, the pe=
ople said. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Soon came the finger-pointin=
g over who was breaking ranks, the people said. Some emerged from the talks=
 suspicious that Credit Suisse wasn=E2=80=99t fully committing to freezing =
sales. By early Friday, rival banks were taking umbrage after hearing that =
Goldman planned to sell some positions, ostensibly to assist Archegos. Morg=
an Stanley began drawing public attention with block trades.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the point I want to make here is that if=
 a bunch of competitors=C2=A0get together on a conference call and agree to=
 limit the supply of some product in order to keep the price of that produc=
t high, that is absolutely a core antitrust violation! That=E2=80=99s the m=
ain bad thing! You can=E2=80=99t do that! Everything in those last three pa=
ragraphs sounds super illegal, if you think of it as, like, chicken produce=
rs trying to reach an agreement not to sell too much chicken to keep the pr=
ice of chicken up, and then =E2=80=9Cfinger-pointing over who was breaking =
ranks=E2=80=9D when one of them sold more chicken.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong, I sympathize with the banks. They reall=
y were hoping to =E2=80=9Chead off the chaos,=E2=80=9D and they failed, and=
 it was chaos, and that chaos was bad and sparked a bunch of investigations=
.=C2=A0(Also, to be clear, a lot of facts have not come out, the banks have=
 good lawyers, and it is entirely possible that the way this all happened w=
as perfectly=C2=A0legal, not collusion among banks about selling stock but =
rather negotiations between the banks and Archegos about the collateral ter=
ms of its swaps.)=C2=A0In general if some cartel of producers colludes to k=
eep supply low and prices high, they will say =E2=80=9Cwe just want the mar=
ket to be orderly,=E2=80=9D and no one will sympathize with them. But in fi=
nancial markets=C2=A0that is much more of a thing: Low volatility=C2=A0<em>=
is=C2=A0</em>sort of a social good, and frankly=C2=A0<em>high prices=C2=A0<=
/em>are popular. If the price of chicken goes down, most people are happy (=
not chicken farmers); if the price of stocks goes down, most people are sad=
. When the banks dumped all their Archegos-linked stocks at fire-sale price=
s, the general reaction was that that was bad. You can understand why they =
wanted to avoid that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So when I read that B=
loomberg story back in March, and I saw phrases like =E2=80=9Cneeded a swif=
t truce =E2=80=A6 to head off billions of dollars in losses for banks and a=
